<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-338-780  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 338 780.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  April 12 1990 v35 n8 p55(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Nix broadcast HDTV. (benefits of high-definition television not inordinary broadcast usage) (editorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Titus, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The development of high-resolution television (HDTV) involves twotechnologies: high resolution displays such as flat-panel monitorsand transmission technology for compressing and expanding videosignals.andP;  A discussion of transmission technology usually focuseson the need to fit HDTV signals into existing 6-MHz broadcasttelevision channels.andP;  A better focus is on the use of fiber-opticstechnology for two-way and other visual communication.andP;  Marketforces should be allowed to push the installation of fiber opticsin homes and businesses for a number of communications uses, notjust television broadcast.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     High definition televisionFiber opticsCommunications TechnologyFuture TechnologiesInteractive Cable.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>